# CDC Library & Spring Boot Starter — Technical Specification

> **Target agent:** Read this document fully before writing any code.  
> **First mandatory step:** Analyse the existing CDC library codebase in its entirety. Identify what is reusable, what must be replaced, and what must be wrapped. Map existing classes to the interfaces defined in this spec before creating anything new. Prefer adaptation over rewrite wherever the logic is sound.

---

## 1. Context & Goals

### 1.1 Background

A colleague has built a POC CDC (Change Data Capture) library that mines an Oracle database using LogMiner. It is a plain Java library with no Spring dependency. It currently:

- Reads a JSON config file (connection details, table list, SQL query, column mappings)
- Creates its own Hikari connection pool from that config
- Executes the provided SQL query against LogMiner, injecting runtime variables (SCN bounds etc.) into it
- Returns change events as results
- Saves an SCN checkpoint internally

### 1.2 Problems with Current Design

| Problem | Impact |
|---|---|
| Owns its own Hikari pool | Duplicate connection pool in host microservice |
| Saves SCN checkpoint independently | Not transactionally safe — checkpoint and inbox write are separate |
| JSON file path config | Cannot be driven by Spring `@ConfigurationProperties` |
| Column mapping baked into JSON config | Not overridable at runtime |
| No defined error handling contract | Silent failures in production |
| No lifecycle hooks | No observability |

### 1.3 Goals

1. **Preserve pure Java usability** — the library must remain usable in a plain Java application with no Spring dependency, exactly as it is today (main method, manual wiring)
2. **Refactor core internals** — replace problematic patterns (own Hikari pool, internal checkpoint) with clean interfaces, while reusing existing LogMiner query logic wherever possible
3. **Create a Spring Boot starter** — provides auto-configuration, `@ConfigurationProperties`, scheduling, health indicator, and Micrometer metrics on top of the core library
4. **Interface-driven design** — every concern that varies across host services is expressed as an interface with a sensible default, overridable via `@ConditionalOnMissingBean` in Spring or constructor injection in pure Java

